# Island Connectivity Hub Website Brief

# Project Overview

The goal of this project is to develop a more comprehensive website for the Island Connectivity Hub.

## Background 

*Mission Statement:* The Island Connectivity Hub is an exciting new regional gathering and learning space, providing community members throughout the Deer Isle-Stonington area with tools, skills, and services needed to thrive in our changing economy through support in workforce pathways and education, digital skill building across disciplines, and health and wellness.

Situated in a historic school building, the Island Connectivity Hub is a collaborative initiative functioning as a central nexus for local organizations and community members. It is founded upon three principal tenets: digital literacy and accessibility, pathways to workforce development (particularly for fishing families navigating transitions), and health and wellness programs. Key partners encompass Deer Isle Adult & Community Education, Project Launch, Haystack Mountain School of Crafts’ Fab Lab, the Northeast Center for Occupational Health & Safety, and local libraries, among others. 

# Project Goals

* Establish an online presence to the Island Connectivity Hub that pairs with the physical hub and allows for a multi-modal/media representation of the resources, content, and partnerships.   
* Phase One: develop a basic content marketing website that can effectively disseminate information and engage the community.   
* Phase Two: Establish an online portal, directory, and web application with advanced features and capabilities. 

# Project Phases

## Phase One: Basic Content Marketing Website & Content Management System

* **Objective**: To establish a preliminary online presence for the Island Connectivity Hub, capable of hosting essential information and promoting community engagement. Content should be able to be added with relative ease and minimal training, with the assumption of some basic knowledge of how websites and the web works.   
* **Key Deliverables (to be finalized during preliminary stakeholder meeting)**:  
  * Responsive website design, optimized for desktop and mobile devices.  
  * Information architecture and navigation structure for basic content.  
  * Content management system (CMS) integration for easy content updates.  
  * Core pages for project introduction, partner information, and contact details.  
  * Basic SEO optimization.  
  * Two years of website hosting and domain setup (see budget section for post-development costs and annual maintenance). 

**Budget:** $3,500 

## Phase Two: Advanced Features and Web Application Development

* **Objective**: To enhance the Island Connectivity Hub website into a comprehensive web application, offering advanced functionalities and interactive resources for the community.  
* **Key Features (TBD)**:  
  * *Community Asset Directory:* a dynamic and exhaustive database of local programs, organizations, opportunities, resources, and other *community resources.* A modern user interface with easy navigation and search or smart features to allow people to discover the resources or opportunities they need when they need them. Resource library with searchable content (documents, links, events).  
  * *Smart Community Calendar*: Interactive calendar of community events.an automated community event aggregation tool that provides a single source of “what’s happening” in the community.  A modern user interface for people to discover events and happenings around the community. Increased connectivity, engagement, etc.   
  * *Digital Partnerships:* Establish a digital network of partners consenting to allow Connectivity Hub’s web app to aggregate and automate the data collection process in a responsible, transparent, and ethical way. This may be both in conjunction with the directory (i.e., does this organization consent to be part of the directory?) as well as the community calendar. Other partnerships may include a shared united authoring platform for easy content entry or proofing and validating automated/aggregated content (i.e., partner site logs in, reviews events pulled into the community calendar and signs off/validates/publishes content to live website).   
  * *Smart Newsletters.* Through digital partnerships, a weekly automated newsletter could be generated to provide social media free communication and broadcasting of news and information about resources, opportunities, etc.   
  * A more robust authoring, content management and database platform for publishing resources, articles, and evergreen content. User accounts and personalized content (if applicable). Integration with relevant community platforms.

**Budget:** TBD (depends on scope and features)

*Please note that Phase Two is fairly ambitious, largely opinionated and defined in terms of my vision for what Digital Connectivity Hub might look like. All of that is subject to change or if determined be developed outside the scope of this project. Some of the ideas described might not be feasible given the current available resources, but could be the premise for future funding, grants, etc. None of this is written in stone; it’s written in a google doc.*

# Technical Considerations & Features 

Specific technical requirements will be finalized during the discovery phase.

## Information Architecture & Content 

We’ll start with the overall architecture of the website and the content to be included. Here are some questions to consider before and as we meet and discuss: 

* What pages or content would be included? For instance, you may want a “Partners” page with a listing of all the Connectivity Hub Partners. About page. Contact page, etc. We’ll talk this through, but start thinking about what content will be included, even if it does not exist yet. Good to plan for the future.   
* What might be the top-level sections? What is the hierarchy of information? For instance, the mission statement might need its own page and is included in the *About* page. 

When organizing the website, we’ll be considering three dimensions: 

* What is the content? *For instance, “we want to include the mission statement in the website”*   
* Where will it be located? *“It’s going to live on the about page.”*  
* How does this information change or update? *“It doesn’t, this is static content.”*

From this, we can develop a site map and structure to the content and information on the website. The design and layout of the website will be informed by both the nature of the content, the architecture and the branding/design guidelines of the connectivity hub. 

## Design 

I do not claim to be a designer, it’s not my area of expertise. However, there are well established design patterns, especially around the web for how content should be displayed. While certain trends have come and gone, there are some best practices I draw upon for design. A couple of considerations and areas of exploration for generating design: 

* Layout is going to be more pre-determined based on the content we are displaying. As such, I will usually make strong recommendations as to how particular should be laid out on the page/screen.   
* Check out website design directories, like [this one](https://land-book.com/) or [dribble](https://dribbble.com/). Look for the things you like or don’t like.   
* Bookmark or save any websites that you want me to use as inspiration or as a template. The more design feedback.   
* There are well established principles of color, typography as it relates to the web. I follow these guidelines whenever possible to ensure that websites meet accessibility standards. I will usually warn or advise against design requests that exceed or conflict with these guidelines. 

In general, we have a great starting point with design because of the work that Samantha did. From this, we’ll be able to create a nice branded marketing style website using a modern web design aesthetic. 

## Content Management 

This will be something we discuss, but there are several options to managing the content on your website. If a website is simple enough and “static” \- meaning the content does not change all that much, then you most likely do not need a Content Management System (CMS). For static websites, you could just write direct HTML or Markdown (a really simple markup format), or use a Graphical User Interface (GUI) editor, often called a *What You See Is What You Get (WYSIWG)* editor to edit the content. Squarespace, Wix, and many other website building platforms offer this type of editor. If you have lots of dynamic content like articles, blogs, newsletters, and so on \- then you’ll want to pick a suitable CMS that integrates with your website. The most famous and ubiquitous is Wordpress, but there are lots of alternatives.

Yes, I can just build a website and target a hosting provider that *you manage* and do a handoff. After the launch and an initial support window to fix bugs, minor tweaks, etc, our contract will terminate and I will no longer be actively managing or monitoring your website. *You will be responsible for renewing your domain with the registrar, pay for hosting fees, and perform basic maintenance or updates*. That said, my goal is to take some of the pain out of dealing with websites and managing them and as such recommend using me as the hosting provider. Rather than some call center or email support queue, you only have to deal with me if anything comes up and I will be actively maintaining your website, renewing fees, all behind the scenes so you don’t have to worry about it. 

## Glossary of Terms 

**Domain** \- a unique human friendly name that will point people to your website. 

**Top-level Domain (TLD)** \- the suffix in a website address (.org, .com, .xyz, .etc). 

**Registrar** \- an approved vendor for distribution and resale of domains. You purchase a domain from a registrar. It is not actually a website.  

**Domain Name Servers (DNS)** \- the traffic controller of the internet; provided a website address (url) it looks up the actual computer address of the server for your website, also known as the IP address. DNS 

**Host** \- the actual service or business that physically controls the server your website is running on. *You* can be a host, and host your own website. Most commonly, we use well established companies that have reliable and scalable infrastructure to host our websites on. Amazon Web Services (AWS), Google Cloud Platform (GCP), Microsoft Azure, and my personal favorite, Cloudflare, are some of the most popular and established host providers in the world. However, there are A LOT of hosts in the world. It’s often bundled together with other services. 

**Website** \- the actual resources, assets, and files that are delivered from your host’s server to a user’s browser and displayed in a human friendly manner. Websites can be really simple and just a bunch of HTML files, or they can be super complicated and use logic and code. 

**Web Applications** \- similar to a website, but usually implies more complexity like user accounts and authentication and databases. Web applications have more moving parts, more resources to manage and take longer to build.
